    <segment id="1" parent="12" relname="background">Ed Morman posted a message to this list recently about a new book by 
Appleby, Hunt, and Jacob.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="concession">  I haven&apos;t read this book yet,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="12" relname="span"> but I have 
corresponded with one of the authors who feels her work has been
mis-used by the Strong Programme.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="16" relname="span">

The Strong Programme strikes me as an excellent example of history taking
science as a model. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="15" relname="span"> In their early days, they made brave claims about 
being inductive. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration"> They cited long lists of scholarly works that they
purported to be the foundation of their interest model.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="14" relname="sequence">  Now the
authors of some of these studies are turning against them. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="concession"> 

The Strong Programme may be out of fashion in science studies today,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="17" relname="span"> but
I still hear echoes of their claims about a growing body of literature
that is supposed to establish something or other. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="19" relname="span"> 

I propose a topic for debate: </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="20" relname="span"> is it better to be able cite a long biblio-
graphy that reflects a broad reading on the part of the author, or to be 
able to critically examine a few articles or books in great depth?</segment>
